    • Enum Constant Detail

      • NONE

        public static final DepotRepository.CacheStrategy NONE
        Completely bypass the cache for this query.

      • BEST

        public static final DepotRepository.CacheStrategy BEST
        Use the SHORT_KEYS strategy if possible, else revert to NONE.

      • RECORDS

        public static final DepotRepository.CacheStrategy RECORDS
        Resolve this collection query in two steps: first we enumerate the primary keys for all the records that satisfy the query, then we acquire the actual data corresponding to each key -- first by consulting the cache, and then only loading from the database the records for the keys that were not located in the cache. Note: This strategy may not be used on @Computed records, for records that do not in fact have a primary key, or for queries that use @FieldOverrides.

      • SHORT_KEYS

        public static final DepotRepository.CacheStrategy SHORT_KEYS
        This strategy is identical to RECORDS, but we also cache the keyset fetched in the first pass. This makes it much more efficient, but also less reliable because there is no invalidation of the keyset query: If records are inserted, deleted or modified, cached keysets will not be updated. Keysets cached using this strategy should have a short time-to-live. Note: This strategy may not be used on @Computed records, for records that do not in fact have a primary key, or for queries that use @FieldOverrides.

      • LONG_KEYS

        public static final DepotRepository.CacheStrategy LONG_KEYS
        This strategy is identical to RECORDS, but we also cache the keyset fetched in the first pass. This makes it much more efficient, but also less reliable because there is no invalidation of the keyset query: If records are inserted, deleted or modified, cached keysets will not be updated. Keysets cached using this strategy may have a long time-to-live. Note: This strategy may not be used on @Computed records, for records that do not in fact have a primary key, or for queries that use @FieldOverrides.

      • CONTENTS

        public static final DepotRepository.CacheStrategy CONTENTS
        This cache strategy is direct and explicit, eschewing the dual phases of the RECORDS and SHORT_KEYS approaches. However, before the database is invoked at all, we consult the cache hoping to find the entire result set already stashed away in there, using the entire query as the key. If we failed to find it, we execute the query and update the cache with the result. This strategy has none of the limitations of SHORT_KEYS and can be used with key-less and @Computed records and arbitrarily complicated queries. Note however that as with SHORT_KEYS, there is no automatic invalidation. It is also potentially very memory intensive.
